# Markdown content conventions

## Naming

| Item | Convention | Example |
|------|------------|---------|
| Guide folder | `kebab-case` | `database-connection-and-security` |
| Include files | `NN-kebab-case.md` (zero-padded) | `15-schema-migration-checklist.md` |
| Sub-articles | `NNA-` prefix | `10A-async-jobs-polling.md` |

## Table of contents (guide README)

- Section heading: `## Table of contents`
- Two-column table: `| # | Topic |` then `|---|-------|`
- Every `includes/*.md` on disk must appear in the TOC (and vice versa)
- Sub-articles labeled under parent (e.g. `10a` under `10`)
- After bulk TOC edits: `python3 scripts/github-format.py`

## Cross-links

| Source | Path to sibling guide |
|--------|------------------------|
| `guide/includes/*.md` | `../../other-guide/...` |
| `guide/README.md` | `../other-guide/...` |

## Acronyms

- First use per file: `ACRONYM(Full Text)` — no space before `(`
- No expansions in `#` headings
- Registry: [acronyms.json](../acronyms.json). Refresh: `python3 scripts/expand-acronyms.py`

## Section structure

- Open with **At a glance** or **Rule of thumb** where helpful
- Capstone/overview sections: `> **Related:**` links to sibling guides
- Overlapping sibling topics: `> **Scope:**` before **Related**
- Use mermaid for flows and architecture
- End with **Common mistakes** / **Pros and cons** when depth warrants
- Every guide README ends with `## See also` (sibling guide table)
- Mid-chapter contextual links use `## Other guides in this repo` — not a duplicate full See also table

